    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>In decorative, open-timber roof trusses, short posts set against the wall, bearing at bottom on a stone corbel or capital and supporting, generally with the aid of a curved brace, the wall end of the tie beam, or hammer beam of the truss. In decorative, open-timber roof trusses, short posts set against the wall, bearing at bottom on a stone corbel or capital and supporting, generally with the aid of a curved brace, the wall end of the tie beam, or hammer beam of the truss.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000077471/Sturgis, Dictionary of Architecture and Building (1901)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>In dekoratie, opengewerkte dakspanten, korte palen die tegen de muur worden geplaatst, aan de voet rustend op een stenen karbeel of kapiteel. Zij ondersteunen, meestal met behulp van een gebogen stut, de muurzijde van de dakbint of van de steekbalk van het gebinte.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
